This appears to be ciphertext encrypted with an Enigma machine. The
illustration shows the connections within each rotor and the reversing
rotor of the machine. It should be noted, however, that the rotor positions
are incorrectly depicted. Actually, rotors 1 and 2 should be interchanged.
The original rotor position, ring position, and connector position are unknown.

The language should be German.

Note that the challenge also has two additional bits of information:

Schlussel
0716150413020110

Schriftzeichen
<the contents of a uuencoded file, which is saved in
uuencoded_stuff_stage08.uue and which I have uudecoded to DEBUGGER.bin>


=============================================================================
SOLUTION NOTES  (decrypt_stage08.py)
=============================================================================

CODEWORD:  PLUTO


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. ARTEFACTS PROVIDED BY THE CHALLENGE
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

a) stage_8_enigma.jpg
   A wiring diagram with six labelled columns:
     Umkehrwalze | Walze 3 | Walze 2 | Walze 1 | Steckerbrett | Tastatur

   Reading each column letter-by-letter and comparing against the published
   Wehrmacht Enigma I rotor catalogue:

     Walze 3 column  ->  matches Rotor III wiring  (BDFHJLCPRTXVZNYEIWGAKMUSQO)
                         turnover notch fires when window = V (position 21)
     Walze 2 column  ->  matches Rotor I  wiring  (EKMFLGDQVZNTOWYHXUSPAIBRCJ)
                         turnover notch fires when window = Q (position 16)
     Walze 1 column  ->  matches Rotor II wiring  (AJDKSIRUXBLHWTMCQGZNPYFVOE)
                         turnover notch fires when window = E (position 4)
     Umkehrwalze     ->  matches Reflector B      (YRUHQSLDPXNGOKMIEBFZCWVJAT)

   The README states "rotors 1 and 2 should be interchanged."  In the image
   Walze 1 is the rightmost (fastest) rotor slot and Walze 2 is the middle
   slot.  After swapping the rotor *types* between those two slots, the
   corrected physical arrangement left -> right is:

       Slot 3 (left / slow)   = Rotor III
       Slot 2 (middle)        = Rotor II   <- was Rotor I in the diagram
       Slot 1 (right / fast)  = Rotor I    <- was Rotor II in the diagram

b) ciphertext_stage08.txt
   367 uppercase letters.  Spaces and line-breaks are formatting only.

c) uuencoded_stuff_stage08.uue / DEBUGGER.BIN
   A UU-encoded 8-byte binary file.  Decoding it yields the hex string:
       34 67 80 fe 5d 4d fc f1
   This is DES("DEBUGGER") encrypted with key 0716150413020110.
   It is a hint for Stage 9, not required to break this Enigma cipher.

d) Schlussel 0716150413020110
   The DES key for Stage 9 (see above).  Also a hint for Stage 9.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. THE ENIGMA MACHINE MODEL
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Each keypress advances the rotors THEN passes the signal through:

  Keyboard -> Plugboard -> Rotor I (right, fast) -> Rotor II (middle)
           -> Rotor III (left, slow) -> Reflector B
           -> Rotor III bwd -> Rotor II bwd -> Rotor I bwd
           -> Plugboard -> Lamp

Stepping rules (evaluated before each keypress):
  * Right rotor always steps.
  * If right rotor's window == its notch letter (Q for Rotor I), the middle
    rotor also steps.
  * If middle rotor's window == its notch letter (E for Rotor II), BOTH the
    middle and left rotors step -- the famous "double-step anomaly".

The Enigma is reciprocal: encrypting a ciphertext with the same starting
state recovers the plaintext.  One function handles both.

Ring setting vs. position:
  The ring setting (Ringstellung) offsets the internal wiring relative to
  the outer lettered ring.  The effective wiring offset for rotor i is
  (position_i - ring_i) mod 26.  The notch, however, is attached to the
  outer ring, so it fires at window_position == notch_letter regardless of
  the ring setting.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. BREAKING THE CIPHER
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 1 -- Find rotor positions using the Index of Coincidence (IoC).

  IoC = sum( n_i*(n_i-1) ) / N*(N-1)
  German text: ~0.076.  Random text: ~0.038.

  When we decrypt with the correct rotors but NO plugboard, the output is
  NOT a simple monalphabetic substitution of the plaintext (the plugboard
  interacts with the rotor wiring in a position-dependent way).  However the
  IoC of the no-stecker output is still noticeably higher than random
  (~0.051 for the correct settings vs ~0.038 for wrong settings), giving a
  clear signal to locate the correct rotor positions.

  We sweep all 17,576 combinations (26^3 starting positions, ring=AAA).
  Peak IoC = 0.0511 found at:
      ring = AAA,  start position = AGL

  Note: ring=AAA/pos=AGL is mathematically equivalent to ring=AZA/pos=AFL
  for this particular 367-character message.  Both give the same effective
  wiring offsets AND the same stepping schedule (the middle rotor's notch
  would only fire around character 604, well past our message length, so
  the left rotor never moves at all).

Step 2 -- Find the plugboard (Steckerbrett) by hill-climbing.

  With the rotor positions fixed at ring=AAA / pos=AGL, we run a greedy
  hill-climb over all possible plugboard pair assignments.

  At each iteration we try connecting every unordered pair of letters (a, b):
    1. Disconnect a and b from their current partners (if any).
    2. Connect a <-> b.
    3. Keep the change if it raises the German bigram/trigram score
       (plus a large bonus for the crib "DASXLOESUNGSWORTXIST" at the start).

  Starting from no pairs (identity plugboard), the search converges on
  restart 0 without any random restarts needed, finding:

      A<->S,  E<->I,  J<->N,  K<->L,  M<->U,  O<->T   (6 pairs)

  The remaining 14 letters (C, D, F, G, H, P, Q, R, V, W, X, Y, Z and B)
  are "unsteckered" (each maps to itself).  A standard Wehrmacht Enigma
  typically uses 10 plugboard pairs; this cipher uses only 6.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. FINAL MACHINE CONFIGURATION
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Rotors (left to right):   III  II  I
  Reflector:                B
  Ring settings (L M R):    A    A   A   (equivalently: A Z A)
  Start positions (L M R):  A    G   L   (equivalently: A F L with ring AZA)
  Plugboard pairs:          AS  EI  JN  KL  MU  OT


